<br>
<br>
<br>
yales: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Quartz is opaque at certain UV frequencies. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, it is very transparent at all UV frequencies.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Also, even if it WERE transparent at those wavelengths, at ~any~ wavelength, the transparency is not nearly 100%. Since Mauk2's design is attempting to transmit 80,000,000,000 watts thru a window 10 square meters in area, just the &quot;normal&quot; transparency will trap enough heat to be Good Night, Irene. <br>
<br>
This is just one of the many fatal flaws of the design.<br>
<br>
There are many other show-stoppers in Mauk's design beyond these.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Maybe if he repeats that &quot;fatal flaws&quot; thing enough, it'll become true!<br>
<br>
In all fairness, if you look at the transmission spectrum I posted above, fused silica has a pretty strong absorption band way down in the infra-red.  Granted, it would be unusual to see anything inside a nuclear light bulb cold enough to radiate way down there...  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Now, in the soft ultraviolet the absorption of fused quartz is miniscule, indeed.  So, the ancient 70's remedy of using silica vapor to absorb the hard UV and re-radiate it at soft UV wavelengths could get the absorption of the lightbulb down well below the pessimistic 2 percent I posted above.<br>
<br>
But this is the NEW MILLENIUM!  Why the heck should we be content with solutions thought up in the last millenium?  Let me draw your attention to the wonderful world of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.research.ibm.com/journal/rd/455/bates.html"> optical research and UV coatings. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The weighty paper I have linked here is from a little outfit called IBM, and if you read through it you will see the immense resources being devoted to materials research in this area.  This is a historic confluence, a marvelous serendipity.  Who would have guessed that research into making computer chips would have been so crucial to opening space in this unexpected way.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
From the single paper I linked above (and I could link many, many more) here are a couple of interesting bits: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  193-nm AR coatings were shown to have transmission exceeding 99% and to withstand 1 × 109 pulses of 15 mJ/cm2/pulse without noticeable degradation <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Target value: Total absorption (1/cm, base 10)  &lt; 0.002    1 × 1011 pulses at 0.5 mJ/cm2/pulse  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Both of the above passages are referring to DEEP UV, way down at 157nm, where the transmission of uncoated silica plunges to nearly zero.  Sure, the power levels are low, but I have no expectations for these lightbulbs to last ten years, either.  Use them four times and you have launched more mass than the US space program has in its entire history!  Doesn't take long at two million pounds a launch....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Given this sort of progress in this field, I feel completely confident in predicting that the actual absorption of a silica lightbulb, over the entire spectrum of interest, with modern manufacturing techniques for the material and modern coatings, would in a launch environment approach or exceed .002 per centimeter of thickness.<br>
<br>
What this means is that if we hold the lightbulb size at 3 meters by 1 meter, with 10 square meters of surface, passing 30,000 Megawatts, then each square meter would have to be cooled of a &quot;mere&quot; 6 megawatts of absorbed energy per centimeter of thickness of the bulb.<br>
<br>
Suddenly, this doesn't seem so bad, does it.  Ain't technology great?  <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> at a realistic thrust to weight ratio it would never lift its own weight. In space it would zoom like a champ (and not cause a radiological disaster in an accident). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
First, without a heavy lift booster, it will never GET to space.  We MUST have a heavy lift booster to do things.  Period.<br>
<br>
Second, as I have stated over, and over, to your repetitious accusations, even a total failure of the booster would be a small release compared to what the USA has ALREADY released into the Pacific with no ill effects.   <br>
<br>
Heck, we could blow up a dozen Liberty Ships in a single year and that would only equal the release from the Castle series of tests in the 1950's.  And the world did not end in the 50's, now did it?<br>
<br>
Am I not being clear when I say this stuff?  Why do I have to keep repeatedly refuting this false rhetoric?<br>
<br>
mylenejenius<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> In looking for alternative materials with similar thermal characteristics to fused silica or quartz I ran into one hell of a show stopper. Fused silica and quartz when exposed to high heat... high UV x-ray and gamma flux... and neutron bombardment will do what is called solarization... in other words it is a discoloration from alteration of the molecular structure. This is a show stopper due to its alteration of transparency and structural properties.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yup, I am aware of the changes neutron bombardment causes, and address this by strictly limiting the exposure lifetime of the silica envelopes.  Heck, if need be we could use new ones on every flight!  Although that may be excessive....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   In other words, this is not a showstopper, its a maintenance issue.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> All I can think of is to perhaps use an alternative fission fuel to uranium... one ideally with a lower boiling point to relax the thermal constrains...  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, no, the efficiency of a nuclear thruster is directly releated to the temperature gradient you can achieve inside it.  IE, the hotter you can run the core without melting the engine, the better off you are.   As it turns out, with todays tech, we can run one REALLY HOT.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Now I have thought of a NLB-VASIMR hybrid... using the NLB to preheat the propellent and to provide power for a VASIMR secondary part of the engine. Using potassium seeded hyrdogen fuel and maybe MHD power generation for additional electrical capacity while under thrust. But as always... I'm not an expert is such things... yet. But I do agree with Yales that the thermal requirements do need to be relaxed. Maybe at some point in the future with further advancements in materials technology Mauk's design might be able to be built... but that time is not today. As such keep working on it Mauk... looks like you just need technology to catch up with where you are. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As I have pointed out in this post, technology is farther along than we think.  We can build this design NOW.  Heck, I think it would not even be all that technically challenging.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for an NLB/VASIMIR hybrid:  Maybe, but that would only be useful in space due to low thrust to weight, and as I said before, FIRST, you have to get to space.  That's the bottleneck.<br>
<br>
The Liberty Ship makes that bottleneck disappear.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
